Gene Ontology (GO) study of the proteome was performed using the functional enrichment and network analysis tool, FunRich (Functional Enrichment Analysis Tool) [13]. Normalised spectral abundance factor (NSAF) was calculated and the proteins were arranged according to the NSAF values. In general, large proteins usually generate more peptides and therefore more spectral counts than smaller proteins. So, the number of spectral counts for each protein needs to be divided by the mass or protein length, which defines the spectral abundance factor (SAF). However, to account for the variability between runs, individual SAF values was normalized to one by dividing by the sum of all SAFs for proteins in the sample, which gives the NSAF value. The NSAF value was calculated as follows:\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
